<preface xml:id="frontmatter-course-overview">
  <title>Course Overview and Navigation</title>

  <section xml:id="course-description">
    <title>Course Description</title>
    <p>
      MATH 2341: Linear Analysis introduces computational and conceptual tools
      from numerical linear algebra and differential equations. The course
      emphasizes mathematical modeling, matrix methods, numerical approximation,
      qualitative behavior of differential equations, and clear communication of
      mathematical reasoning.
    </p>

    <p>
      Edit this paragraph to match the official Cal Poly catalog description,
      your departmental expectations, and your specific course emphasis.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="how-to-use-this-book">
    <title>How to Use This Book</title>
    <p>
      This online book is organized into three main parts:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <em>Weekly Course Notes</em> contain the definitions, examples, theorems,
          and worked computations for each week.
        </li>
        <li>
          <em>Weekly In-Class Activities</em> contain collaborative activities for
          class meetings.
        </li>
        <li>
          <em>Weekly Problem Sets</em> contain the assignments connected to each
          week&apos;s material.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      Use the table of contents to jump between weeks. The search box is useful
      when you remember a phrase but not the location. The index at the end of
      the book collects important terms, notation, and methods. For example,
      entries such as <idx>row reduction</idx>row reduction,
      <idx>basis</idx>basis, <idx>Euler&apos;s method</idx>Euler&apos;s method, and
      <idx>eigenvalue</idx>eigenvalue can be added throughout the notes.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="notation-and-technology">
    <title>Notation and Technology</title>
    <p>
      Vectors are usually written as <m>\vect{v}</m>, matrices as
      <m>\mat{A}</m>, and real coordinate spaces as <m>\R^n</m>. Computational
      cells, when included, are meant to support mathematical understanding.
      Students are not expected to learn a separate programming language unless
      explicitly stated.
    </p>
  </section>
</preface>
